 in Italy."],"variants":[{"name":"Foglio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmine, Dino, Flavio, Julieta, Sal, Salvatore.","Italian: probably from the Latin personal name <i>Folius</i> (which is embodied in the common placename Fogliano)."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":55,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":64,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Maud Foliot was born in 1160, in Woodford, Northamptonshire, England. She had at least 1 son with Hugh de Hynton of Hinton-Woodford. She died in 1240, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1160–1240":"1160–1240","1190–1253":"1190–1253","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1253":"1253","1240":"1240","1160":"1160","about 1240":"umbes 1240","Woodford, Northamptonshire, England":"Woodford, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1160–1240":"1160–1240","1190–1253":"1190–1253","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1253":"1253","1240":"1240","1160":"1160","about 1240":"noin 1240","Woodford, Northamptonshire, England":"Woodford, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1160–1240":"1160–1240","1190–1253":"1190–1253","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1253":"1253","1240":"1240","1160":"1160","about 1240":"environ 1240","Woodford, Northamptonshire, England":"Woodford, Northamptonshire, Anglet